Implemented Vercel Speed Insights for Next.js

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the EduPod Next.js application. This implementation adds real-time performance monitoring capabilities to track Core Web Vitals and other speed metrics.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights` version 1.3.1 using npm
- Updated package.json dependencies to include the new package
- Updated package-lock.json with resolved dependencies

### 2. Code Changes
**Modified: src/app/layout.tsx**
- Added import statement: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next"`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag, placed after the main application content (children wrapped in AuthProvider and SettingsProvider)

## Implementation Details

This project uses:
- Next.js 16.0.10 (App Router)
- npm as the package manager
- TypeScript

Since the project uses Next.js 16.0.10 (which is newer than 13.5) with the App Router architecture, I used the recommended approach for modern Next.js applications:
1. Imported SpeedInsights from `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
2. Added the component directly to the root layout at `src/app/layout.tsx`
3. Placed it inside the `<body>` tag after the main application content

The component will automatically track:
- First Contentful Paint (FCP)
- Largest Contentful Paint (LCP)
- Cumulative Layout Shift (CLS)
- First Input Delay (FID)
- Interaction to Next Paint (INP)
- Time to First Byte (TTFB)

## Testing & Verification

✅ ESLint check passed for layout.tsx (no errors introduced)
✅ TypeScript compilation successful
✅ Package installation completed successfully
✅ Lock files updated appropriately

Note: The full build process encountered an unrelated error due to missing Supabase environment variables (.env file), which is a pre-existing configuration issue not related to this implementation. The TypeScript compilation step completed successfully before the build failed on the prerendering step.

## Files Modified
1. `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights dependency
2. `package-lock.json` - Updated with new package resolution
3. `src/app/layout.tsx` - Added SpeedInsights component import and usage

All changes follow Next.js best practices and maintain the existing code structure and patterns.
